1.2. Generate random colours¶

In [2]:
def random_color(no_of_colors): # Function returns a list of defined number of colours
    color=["#"+''.join([random.choice('0123456789ABCDEF') for i in range(6)])
           for j in range(no_of_colors)]
    return color

1.6. Finding the optimal locations for three drone depots using k-means clustering¶

In [8]:
num_clusters = 3 # Define the number of clusters to form as well as the number of centroids to generate

# Form three clusters based on clients location from the centroids using K-means algorithm, consider the following parameters
# The number of clusters (n_clusters) is 3
# ‘k-means++’ to select initial cluster centroids by making several trials at each sampling step to choose the best centroid
# Maximum number of iterations of the k-means algorithm for a single run is 300
# Relative tolerance with regards to Frobenius norm is 0.0001
# Verbosity mode is 0
kmeans = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters = num_clusters, init='k-means++', max_iter=300,  tol=0.0001, verbose=0)

start_time = time.time() # Retrieve the time at this moment and assign it to variable start_time
kmeans.fit(df_scaled) # Take the training data df as arguments
end_time = time.time() # Retrieve the time at this moment and assign it to variable end_time
computation_time_3clusters = end_time - start_time # Calculate computation time and assign the result to variable computation_time

centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_ # Get three centroids in 2-dimensional feature space and assign it to arry centroids
centroids_df_scaled = pd.DataFrame(centroids, columns=column_labels) # Create dataframe for centroids, add x, y as column labels  

print(f' The three drone depots:\n{centroids_df_scaled}') # Print centroids dataframe
print(f'The number of iterations for convergence: {kmeans.n_iter_}') # Print iterations number
print(f'Computation time for three clusters is {computation_time_3clusters}') # Print computation time

4.2. Conclusion¶

For clusters [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 , 15, 18, 20]

the corresponding times were

[0.09574270248413086, 0.1466076374053955, 0.18350648880004883, 0.16754984855651855, 0.18749547004699707, 0.24235153198242188, 0.3181438446044922, 0.45478034019470215, 0.41687560081481934, 0.4777195453643799, 0.5764579772949219, 0.5006582736968994]

The computation time is directly proportional to the number of clusters in unstable proportion.

The computation time was increasing slightly for small numbers of clusters, but when using big number (above 200) the change in computation time was much bigger.

5.2. Observations after trying various depot numbers¶

  • Agglomerative hierarchical clustering produced clustering solutions of lower entropy than k-means, unlike k-means solusions.

  • The behavior of agglomerative hierarchical clustering is slightly superior than k-means in terms of clustering solution in quality and purity.

  • Agglomerative hierarchical clustering computation time was slower comparing with K-means which was faster, so for very large datasets, this can be slow.

  • The main observation is that the agglomerative hierarchical clustering algorithm works faster when crearing a big number of clusters. It also creates different classes than kmeans algorithm, which can be seen when comparing both algorithms to create the same number of clusters.

  • Agglomerative hierarchical clustering solutions are not shaped in hyper spherical unlike k-means
